'''Circus Juventas''' (formerly '''Circus of the Star''') is a youth [[performing arts]] [[circus]] school located in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota]], and serving [[youth]] throughout the [[Minneapolis-Saint Paul]] metropolitan area. The organization was founded in 1994 by Dan and Betty Butler, and offers [[circus arts]] training to young people ranging in age from 3<U+2013>21.

Emulating the style of [[Cirque du Soleil]], Circus Juventas's first show was at Saint Paul's Highland Fest in 1995. From there, the school's enrollment quickly expanded and the organization initiated a campaign to fund a $2.1 million permanent [[big top (circus)|big top]] facility which opened in 2001 on Saint Paul parkland in the [[Highland Park, Saint Paul|Highland Park neighborhood]]. That year, it began to produce annual summer performances showcasing the work of its most advanced students, each with a distinct theme. 

These shows have proven popular with local audiences and have been well received critically, with reviewers praising the professionalism and fearlessness exhibited in the productions, while noting the occasional mishap of the school's performers. In addition, Circus Juventas students have performed and competed both around the Minneapolis-Saint Paul area and abroad. Today, Juventas is the largest youth performing arts circus in North America and it has tentative plans to add a second facility elsewhere in the region.

==History==
Dan and Betty Butler met as teenagers at the Sailor Circus of [[Sarasota, Florida|Sarasota]] during the mid-1970s.<ref name="wapo">{{cite news|last=Forliti|first=Amy|title=Minn. Circus School Helps Kids Fly High|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/07/07/AR2007070700186.html|accessdate=July 19, 2010|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=July 7, 2007}}</ref> Dan was a catcher on the [[flying trapeze]], while Betty was an aerialist on the [[cloud swing]].<ref name="donor">{{cite news|last=Meier|first=Peg|title=A show of generosity - Anonymous St. Paul donor gives $60,000 for youth circus building|accessdate=June 17, 2014|newspaper=[[Star Tribune]]|date=August 9, 1999|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/427165290}}{{subscription required|via=ProQuest}}</ref> They began dating at age sixteen<ref name=donor /> and both went on to perform at [[Florida State University]]'s [[FSU Flying High Circus|Flying High Circus]].<ref name=wapo /> Dan became a successful real estate broker in [[Atlanta]], but eventually faced bankruptcy and chemical dependency.<ref name=donor /> The couple came to reside in [[Minnesota]] because Dan Butler was receiving alcohol and drug abuse rehabilitation at [[Hazelden]].<ref name=wapo /> The Butlers attended Sailor Circus reunions together and after one, in April 1994, Betty Butler wondered, "Wouldn't it be great if we could do something in {{nowrap|Minnesota ...}}"<ref name=UBT>{{cite news|last1=Tomson|first1=Ellen|title=Under the Big Top|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com.ezproxy.hclib.org/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=AWNB&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=0EDCE2B524F0C2C3&p_docnum=19&p_queryname=5|accessdate=June 19, 2014|work=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|date=August 5, 2001}}{{subscription required|via=NewsBank}}</ref>

[[File:Hillcrest Recreation Center 2013.jpg|thumb|left|Hillcrest Recreation Center, the original home of Circus Juventas (then Circus of the Star)|alt=A beige building with a large windowed rotunda stands before a large lawn]]
The Butlers founded Circus Juventas as a [[non-profit corporation]] in October 1994,{{sfn|Wall|2013|p=303}}<ref name=fund-raiser>{{cite news|title=Fund-raiser held for circus|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com.ezproxy.hclib.org/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=AWNB&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=0EB5E231AF0957DF&p_docnum=5&p_queryname=3|accessdate=June 19, 2014|work=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|date=October 30, 1997}}{{subscription required|via=NewsBank}}</ref> citing a desire to give back to the community as one of the reasons for its creation.<ref name=wapo /> It was originally known as Circus of the Star, so-called for Minnesota's [[List of U.S. state nicknames|nickname]], The North Star State.<ref name=donor />  The newly opened Hillcrest Recreation Center in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|Saint Paul]] provided the couple with inspiration for the circus program, and they asked the city if they could hold classes there.<ref name="center">{{cite news|last=Kimball|first=Joe|title=Circus puts kids in the center ring|accessdate=July 19, 2010|newspaper=[[Star Tribune]]|date=August 4, 1997|accessdate=June 17, 2014|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/426871333}}{{subscription required|via=ProQuest}}</ref> The Saint Paul Parks and Recreation Department approved the program, and assumed liability for approximately fifty children who enrolled the first year.<ref name="center" /> About thirty of those students stayed with the program and performed in their first show<ref name="center" /> at the 1995 Highland Fest, an annual family-oriented festival.<ref name="history">{{cite web|title=History|url=http://www.circusjuventas.org/index.php/about-us/history|publisher=Circus Juventas|accessdate=July 19, 2010|year=2009}}</ref> After this performance, interest in the program increased.<ref name=history /> By 1996, around thirty more students were enrolled, and by 1997, an additional twenty-five had joined the program.<ref name=center /> The circus was still based out of the Hillcrest Recreation Center's gym, and had to work around the schedule of the other regular activities in the facility.<ref name=center /> In 1997, the waitlist for the program was around 200 students.<ref name=center />

With the school's growing popularity, the Butlers saw the need for a larger space so they developed plans to build a 1,500-seat facility.<ref name=hitches>{{cite news|last1=Tomson|first1=Ellen|title=Kids' Circus Hitches Its Wagon to a Star|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=NewsBank&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=0EB5E1C6CFE4B2EA&p_docnum=4&p_queryname=2|accessdate=June 18, 2014|work=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|date=July 5, 1997}}{{subscription required|via=NewsBank}}</ref> In an article published in the ''[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]'' in 1997, the estimated cost of the project was quoted at $700,000 with a groundbreaking planned for April 1998.<ref name=hitches /> The Butlers kicked off their capital campaign on February 18, 1998, with the goal of raising $1.1 million for their new building.<ref name="new home">{{cite news|last1=Kimball|first1=Joe|title=Ramsey County Fair to uproot - this year |url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/426943707|accessdate=June 17, 2014|work=[[Star Tribune]]|date=February 20, 1998}}{{subscription required|via=ProQuest}}</ref> By August 1999, they had raised $1 million of their expanded $1.6 million goal for the circus expansion, with plans to break ground on the new facility that November.<ref name=donor /> Part of the funding came from Saint Paul's Sales Tax Revitalization (STAR) program, through which surplus funds were distributed by councilmembers to worthy organizations.<ref name=slush>{{cite news|last1=Coleman|first1=Toni|title=Council cash called slush fund|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/463631864|accessdate=June 17, 2014|work=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|agency=Knight Ridder Tribune Business News|date=March 21, 2005}}{{subscription required|via=ProQuest}}</ref> A total of $627,183 were disbursed for the circus through the program, split between three STAR components: $450,000 as part of Neighborhood STAR which sought to fund neighborhood initiatives, $122,183 as part of Cultural STAR which funded arts and culture programs, and $55,000 from 3rd Ward City Councilmember Pat Harris's discretionary Neighborhood Investment Initiative budget.<ref name=slush /> Another $60,000 came from an anonymous recently retired Saint Paul businessperson.<ref name=donor />

[[File:Circus Juventas ext.jpg|thumb|right|The permanent big top facility, exterior]]
The $1.6 million were raised in full by the end of April 2000, just in time to ensure the circus received its STAR funding which would have been nullified if the Butlers hadn't made their fundraising goal by May 5 of that year.<ref name="juggles its way">{{cite news|last1=Burson|first1=Pat|title=Circus juggles its way to success|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com.ezproxy.hclib.org/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=AWNB&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=0EB739AF36AFAD0A&p_docnum=16&p_queryname=5|accessdate=June 19, 2014|work=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|date=April 29, 2000}}{{subscription required|via=NewsBank}}</ref> The Butlers had found the space for the school through coincidence; after driving along Montreal Avenue in Saint Paul one night, they turned into a parking lot, noticed an area beneath some trees, and realized it was an ideal location for their school's expanded facility.<ref name=UBT /> On August 25, 2000, ground was broken on the new structure.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kimball|first1=Joe|title=State Fair's real animals are no competition for Snoopy|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/427307229|accessdate=June 18, 2014|work=[[Star Tribune]]|date=August 25, 2000}}{{subscription required|via=ProQuest}}</ref> The big top took about a year to complete, during which time the school also changed its name to Circus Juventas, named for [[Juventas]], an ancient Roman goddess of youth and rejuvenation.<ref name=UBT /> Ultimately, the project totaled $2.1 million<ref name=UBT /> and by 2006, the school was $700,000 in debt.<ref name=balancing>{{cite news|last1=Peiken|first1=Matt|title=Balancing act for Circus Juventas|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/465184465|accessdate=June 20, 2014|work=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|agency=McClatchy-Tribune Business News|date=July 28, 2006}}{{subscription required|via=ProQuest}}</ref> It was, however, working with various city agencies to resolve the issue and faced "no looming threat".<ref name=balancing /> The school relies heavily on parent volunteers to help with various operational aspects, from [[rigging (theatre)|rigging]] to administrative work to set construction and decoration.<ref name=contagion>{{cite news|last1=Jefferson|first1=Jennifer|title=The Circus Contagion|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com.ezproxy.hclib.org/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=AWNB&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=0FCC7F9D0D326DFC&p_docnum=20&p_queryname=2|accessdate=June 20, 2014|work=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|date=August 6, 2003}}{{subscription required|via=NewsBank}}</ref> Betty Butler estimated that 90% of work on the school's shows is done by parent volunteers.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Beckstrom|first1=Maja|title=At Circus Juventas, Parents Are Part of the Crew|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com.ezproxy.hclib.org/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=AWNB&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=10BCC4E5021470B0&p_docnum=27&p_queryname=2|accessdate=June 20, 2014|work=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|date=July 31, 2005}}{{subscription required|via=NewsBank}}</ref> The circus operates with the equivalent of 40 full-time employees.<ref name=villager>{{cite news|last1=McKenzie|first1=James|title=Juventas at 20|work=[[Villager]]|date=July 23 <U+2013> August 5, 2014|page=5}}</ref>

As of 2010, the circus school enrolled students from ages six to 21, with an additional enrollment of about 150 toddlers and other younger participants{{sfn|Rowe|2010|loc=13:46}} as young as three years old.{{sfn|Rea|2012|p=123}} By 2013, the enrollment had reached over 800 and the school's annual operating budget exceeded $2 million.{{sfn|Wall|2013|p=303}} Circus Juventas has also held circus arts fitness classes for adults, taught by the school's regular instructors.<ref>{{cite news|last=Read|first=Katy|title=Try this: Circus arts|url=http://www.startribune.com/lifestyle/balance/137038233.html|accessdate= March 24, 2014|newspaper=[[Star Tribune]]|date=January 10, 2012}}</ref> The school is a member of the Outdoor Amusement Business Association and the F<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ration Mondiale du Cirque.<ref name="expanding spectacle">{{cite news|last1=Jando|first1=Dominique|title=Circus Juventas Expanding in all Directions|url=http://spectaclemagazine.com/?page_id=4754|accessdate=June 16, 2014|work=Spectacle: An Online Journal of Circus Arts|date=April 2014}}</ref> A listing on the latter organization's website notes that as of 2014, Juventas is the largest performing arts circus school for youth in the United States;<ref>{{cite web|title=Fifth World Circus Day, 19 April 2014|url=http://www.circusfederation.org/2014_wcd/557|publisher=Federation Mondiale du Cirque|accessdate=June 24, 2014|year=2014}}</ref> other sources indicate that it is the largest in all of North America.<ref name=villager /><ref name="knight oz">{{cite web|last1=Schouweiler|first1=Susannah|title=Circus Juventas heads over the rainbow for their summer show, "OZ!"|url=http://www.knightarts.org/community/stpaul/circus-juventas-heads-over-the-rainbow-for-their-summer-show-oz|website=Knight Arts|publisher=John S. and James L. Knight Foundation|accessdate=July 19, 2014|date=July 31, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=''Pioneer Press'' staff|title=Tickets for Circus Juventas summer show announced|url=http://www.twincities.com/allheadlines/ci_20890920/tickets-circus-juventas-summer-show-announced|accessdate=October 4, 2014|work=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|date=June 19, 2012}}</ref>

== Facilities ==
Circus Juventas's big top is located in the [[Highland Park, Saint Paul|Highland Park neighborhood]] of Saint Paul, Minnesota.<ref name="minnpost">{{cite news|last=Kimball|first=Joe|title=Circus Juventas youth circus to perform in St. Paul July 30 to Aug. 16|url=http://www.minnpost.com/artsarena/2009/07/13/10213/circus_juventas_youth_circus_to_perform_in_st_paul_july_30_to_aug_16|newspaper=[[MinnPost]]|accessdate=July 19, 2010|date=July 13, 2009}}</ref> It stands {{convert|40|ft|m|0}} tall and encompasses {{convert|21000|sqft|m2|0}} of floor space<ref name=peek>{{cite news|last1=Kimball|first1=Joe|title=Taking a peek under St. Paul's new Big Top|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/427395508|accessdate=June 19, 2014|work=[[Star Tribune]]|date=April 27, 2001}}{{subscription required|via=ProQuest}}</ref> built on [[concrete slab]].{{sfn|LeFevre|2003|p=40}} The structure is supported by an [[aluminum]] frame and covered with flame-resistant [[Polyvinyl chloride|vinyl]]-coated cloth.<ref name=donor /> The building's {{convert|1000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} lobby space was designed by Locus Architecture, Ltd. of Minneapolis.{{sfn|LeFevre|2003|p=40}} The firm connected [[texteline]] fabric (often used for awnings) to the system of catwalks and supports to help "the lobby act...as an immersion tank, rather than a threshold, to introduce spectators to the illusion of the world of circus."{{sfn|LeFevre|2003|p=41}} Although Locus was still installing the fabric within hours of the circus's gala opening,{{sfn|LeFevre|2003|p=41}} the company won one of the 10 honor awards distributed in 2002 by the Minnesota branch of the [[American Institute of Architects]] for their design.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mack|first1=Linda|title=HGA wins 4 of 10 Minnesota architecture Honor Awards|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/427518099|accessdate=July 19, 2014|work=[[Star Tribune]]|date=November 14, 2002}}{{subscription required|via=ProQuest}}</ref> The circus school's original bleachers could seat 1,200 audiencemembers.<ref name=peek />

===Bleacher collapse===
[[File:CJ bleacher collapse.jpg|thumb|right|The bleachers shortly after the collapse]]
On August 16, 2009, at the closing performance of the show ''Yulong'', a set of bleachers with a carrying capacity of 450 people and holing 420 at the time collapsed, sending seven people to the hospital.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kaiser|first1=Emily|title=Circus Juventas bleachers collapse during final performance, 450 people fall|url=http://blogs.citypages.com/blotter/2009/08/circus_juventas.php|accessdate=June 24, 2014|work=[[City Pages]]|date=August 17, 2009}}</ref><ref name=fellpp>{{cite news|last1=Gottfried|first1=Mara H.|last2=Olson|first2=Jeremy|title=City inspectors will examine bleachers where 420 fell at St. Paul youth circus|url=http://www.twincities.com/news/ci_13142234|accessdate=June 24, 2014|work=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|date=August 19, 2009}}</ref> In the ensuing investigation, it came to light that Juventas had not had the bleachers inspected each time they were set up, as required by their lease with the city.<ref name=mpr_fined>{{cite news|last=Nelson|first=Tim|title=Circus Juventas fined for not getting bleachers inspected|url=http://minnesota.publicradio.org/display/web/2009/08/20/circus-bleacher-collapse/|accessdate=November 20, 2012|newspaper=All Things Considered|date= August 20, 2009|agency=[[Minnesota Public Radio]]}}</ref> They had been issued a permit in 2006 for the bleachers, and had not had them inspected since.<ref name=fellpp /> The school was fined $500 and shut down until the legal and safety issues could be fully investigated.<ref name=mpr_fined /> It reopened about a month later<ref>{{cite news|last1=Holmquist|first1=Alex|title=Circus Juventas to resume classes Saturday|url=http://www.twincities.com/alllistings/ci_13353259|accessdate=June 24, 2014|work=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|date=September 17, 2009}}</ref> and installed new bleachers with molded plastic seats the next March.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ziegler|first1=Suzanne|title=Supersize seating coming to a theater near you|url=http://www.startribune.com/lifestyle/98614254.html|accessdate=June 24, 2014|work=[[Star Tribune]]|date=July 16, 2010}}</ref>

===Future===
In early 2014, the Butlers announced plans to expand their big top facility by an additional {{convert|10000|sqft|m2}}.<ref name="expanding spectacle" /> The additional space will house a dance and theater studio, a costume shop, offices, and a {{convert|4500|sqft|m2|adj=on}} gym.<ref name="expanding spectacle" /> Naming rights for the new structure will provide a component of the $4 million the school hopes to raise for the $2 million expansion, a $1 million addition to the circus's endowment, and eventual repairs to the building's exterior, estimated at $1 million.<ref name="expanding spectacle" /> Betty Butler stated that the project stemmed from the desire to create "a true professional program, a separate program" for students looking to study and perform circus arts post-Juventas, even though she and her husband originally shied away from pre-professional training as a core aspect of their circus school.<ref name="expanding spectacle" />

According to Saint Paul's Parks and Recreation Department, the cliffside space which the expansion would occupy is unsuitable for building a structure of the expansion's proposed size.<ref name=fighting>{{cite news|last1=Duchschere|first1=Kevin|title=Fighting with St. Paul, Circus Juventas hunts for new home|url=http://www.startribune.com/local/west/268673032.html?page=all|accessdate=July 26, 2014|work=[[Star Tribune]]|date=July 26, 2014}}</ref> In response, the Butlers are considering building a new facility of up to {{convert|50000|sqft|m2}} in the western suburbs of Minneapolis<U+2013>Saint Paul.<ref name=fighting /> Construction of a new building would likely cost $10 million and would require a capital campaign to fund<ref name=fighting /> and would likely not begin for five to 10 years.<ref name=staying>{{cite news|last1=Combs|first1=Marianne|title=Circus Juventas: <U+2018>We<U+2019>re staying in St. Paul<U+2019>|url=http://blogs.mprnews.org/state-of-the-arts/2014/07/circus-juventas-were-staying-in-st-paul/|accessdate=August 1, 2014|work=MPR News|agency=[[Minnesota Public Radio]]|date=July 30, 2014}}</ref> In the meantime, the school is performing a small expansion to their Highland Park space, on which the Circus has a lease for at least 17 more years, as of 2014.<ref name=staying />

==Performances==
[[File:Circus Juventas big top interior, August 2014.jpg|thumb|right|Inside the big top after a ''Neverland'' show in 2014|alt=A large big top space with a back wall painted like a massive treehouse and bleachers on each side. The space is lit florescently and people mill about.]]
The school typically puts on two shows per year: a spring performance featuring less advanced students studying circus arts at beginning and intermediate levels, and a late summer show to display the talents of more advanced students.<ref name=knightarts>{{cite web|last=Schouweiler|first=Susannah|title=Circus Juventas<U+2019> "Grimm" enchants|url=http://www.knightarts.org/community/stpaul/circus-juventas-grimm-enchants|work=Knight Arts|publisher=John S. and James L. Knight Foundation|accessdate=November 20, 2012|date=August 1, 2011}}</ref> While the earliest shows were focused primarily on technique and the individual acts, by 1997 or 1998 the school began to put more focus into the artistic side of performances, including integrating said acts into [[Cirque du Soleil]]-style narratives, according to Dan Butler.{{sfn|Rowe|2010|loc=14:02}}

===Big top summer shows===
* 2001: ''Mythos'', a production dealing with [[Greek mythology]]<ref name=UBT /> that was performed not only in Circus Juventas's new permanent big top facility but also at the [[Minnesota State Capitol]] on New Year's Eve, 2001.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kimball|first1=Joe|title=Butler on the mend|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/427429312|accessdate=June 16, 2014|work=[[Star Tribune]]|date=July 27, 2001}}{{subscription required|via=ProQuest}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Harlow|first1=Tim|title=Diversions; Capital New Year|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/427459078|accessdate=June 16, 2014|work=[[Star Tribune]]|date=December 30, 2001}}{{subscription required|via=ProQuest}}</ref>
* 2002: ''Cirque Napoleon'', a show that delved into the history of circus, taking place in a French circus in 1859 and honoring [[Jules L<U+00E9>otard]], an early trapeze artist.<ref name="little big top">{{cite news|last1=Shah|first1=Allie|title=Little Big Top; Kids in St. Paul's Highland Park don't have to run away to join the circus|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/427503934|accessdate=June 16, 2014|work=[[Star Tribune]]|date=August 9, 2002}}{{subscription required|via=ProQuest}}</ref>
* 2003: ''Taroq'', a production set in Morocco following four traveling nomads on a quest to determine the meaning of life.<ref name=parents>{{cite news|last1=Jefferson|first1=Jennifer|title=Circus Contagion Hits St. Paul, Minn., Parents|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/464231120|accessdate=June 16, 2014|work=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|agency=Knight Ridder Tribune Business News|date=August 6, 2003}}{{subscription required|via=ProQuest}}</ref> 
* 2004: ''Swash'', a pirate-themed performance that entailed a quest for lost treasure.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Boyd|first1=Melissa D.|title=This Week's Best Bets; Diversions; Circus Juventas|url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/427649208|accessdate=June 16, 2014|work=[[Star Tribune]]|date=August 6, 2004}}{{subscription required|via=ProQuest}}</ref>
* 2005: ''Dyrnwych'', a production that included "an amalgam of fairy-tale types, with wicked hag witches, trolls, forest spirits, and warrior women."<ref>{{cite news|last=Skinner|first=Quinton|title=Spotlight: Dyrnwych|url=http://www.citypages.com/2005-08-03/arts/spotlight-dyrnwych/full/|accessdate=April 26, 2014|newspaper=[[City Pages]]|date=April 3, 2005}}</ref>
* 2006: ''Pazzanni'', a retelling of the story of [[Cinderella]],<ref name=balancing /> inspired by 1500s [[Venice|Venetian]] [[carnivale]]s and featuring masks designed by the maskmaker responsible for those used in the 1999 film ''[[Eyes Wide Shut]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Pazzanni|url=http://www.rakemag.com/2006/07/pazzanni/|accessdate=April 26, 2014|newspaper=The Rake|date=July 31, 2006|author=Staff}}</ref>
* 2007: ''Atlanticus'', a performance set under the oceans in the domain of [[Poseidon]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Try doing this|url=http://www.camdenews.org/news/info.nsf/get+CCN+Article+All/Arts_Try+doing+this|accessdate=April 26, 2014|newspaper=Camden Community News|date=July 1, 2007|author=Staff}}</ref> 
* 2008: ''RavensManor'', a [[haunted house]]-themed show, based loosely on the [[Haunted Mansion]] ride located in [[Disneyland]].<ref name="dompap raven">{{cite news|last=Papatola|first=Dominic P.|title=Hey, Big Guy, Step Away From the Spotlight; Smaller Productions Coming Through|accessdate=February 8, 2013|newspaper=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|date=July 6, 2008|url=http://infoweb.newsbank.com/iw-search/we/InfoWeb?p_product=AWNB&p_theme=aggregated5&p_action=doc&p_docid=121CC24E1D1EB258&d_place=PIPB&f_issue=2008-07-06&f_publisher=}}{{subscription required|via=NewsBank}}</ref> ''RavensManor''{{'}}s story, set in New Orleans, included a tragic romance and zombies.<ref name="MP RavensManor">{{cite news|last=Walsh|first=Jim|title=Of the circus (go), Westerberg, the Joker's chaos and more ...|url=http://www.minnpost.com/arts-culture/2008/08/circus-go-westerberg-jokers-chaos-and-more|accessdate=February 8, 2013|newspaper=[[MinnPost]]|date= August 4, 2008}}</ref><ref name=PJtC>{{Cite AV media notes |title=Peter Joins the Circus: Original and arranged music by Peter Ostroushko for Circus Juventas 2005-2008 |others=[[Peter Ostroushko]] |year=2008 |first=Peter |last=Ostroushko| last2=Butler | first2=Betty|last3=Butler|first3=Dan |type=Liner notes |publisher=Borderland Productions |id= |location=Minneapolis}}</ref>
* 2009: ''Yulong: The Jade Dragon'' (sometimes shortened to ''Yulong''), a presentation derived from Chinese legendary and circus traditions. Produced in collaboration with the Chinese American Association of Minnesota, the show spotlighted three Taiwanese guest artists and included an emphasis on Chinese circus acts such as [[Chinese pole]] and hoop diving.<ref name=huyck>{{cite news|last=Huyck|first=Ed|title=Circus Juventas, plus Taiwanese guest artists, present 'Yulong'|url=http://www.minnpost.com/arts-arena/2009/07/circus-juventas-plus-taiwanese-guest-artists-present-yulong|accessdate=November 20, 2012|newspaper=[[MinnPost]]|date=July 29, 2009}}</ref>
* 2010: ''Sawdust'', a performance evoking the traditions of historic American circuses. Special guests in the show were veteran circus performers Willie Edleston and Tony Steele who played slightly fictionalized versions of themselves.<ref name=BTSsawdust>{{cite news|last=Gabler|first=Jay|title=Circus Juventas gathers "Sawdust"|url=http://www.tcdailyplanet.net/news/2010/07/20/circus-juventas-gathers-sawdust|accessdate=November 20, 2012|newspaper=Twin Cities Daily Planet|date=July 20, 2010}}</ref> 
* 2011: ''Grimm<U+2014>Happily Ever After!''<ref name=BTSgrimm>{{cite news|last=Do|first=Trang|title=Behind the scenes as Circus Juventas rehearses "Grimm<U+2014>Happily Ever After!"|url=http://www.tcdailyplanet.net/arts/circus-juventas-grimm-photos|accessdate=November 20, 2012|newspaper=Twin Cities Daily Planet|date=July 28, 2011}}</ref> (sometimes shortened to ''Grimm''), a show retelling a number of the [[Brothers Grimm]]'s fairy tales. Characters included [[Rapunzel]], [[Cinderella]], [[Little Red Riding Hood]], [[Hansel and Gretel]], [[Snow White]], and the [[The Frog Prince (story)|Frog Prince]].<ref name=knightarts /> 
* 2012: ''Showdown'', a [[Wild West]]-themed show set in the fictional town of Tumbleweed.<ref name=tumbleweedtumbles>{{cite news|last=Preston|first=Rohan|title=In this show, Tumbleweed really tumbles|url=http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/stageandarts/165741756.html|accessdate=November 20, 2012|newspaper=[[Star Tribune]]|date=August 10, 2012}}</ref> The performance included portrayals of real outlaws, lawmen, and singers, including [[Lillie Langtry]],<ref name=youngfearless>{{cite news|last=Bankston|first=Amanda|title=The Young and the Fearless|url=http://www.minnesotamonthly.com/media/Blogs/Twin-Cities-Culture/August-2012/The-Young-and-the-Fearless/|accessdate=November 20, 2012|newspaper=Minnesota Monthly|date=August 6, 2012}}</ref> [[Black Bart (outlaw)|Black Bart]], [[Billy the Kid]], and [[Wyatt Earp]], and featured a seven-man highwire pyramid, becoming the second youth circus to complete this trick.<ref name=SDspotlight>{{cite news|last=Royce|first=Graydon|title=Onstage spotlight: Circus Juventas|url=http://www.startribune.com/entertainment/stageandarts/163943376.html|accessdate=November 20, 2012|newspaper=[[Star Tribune]]|date=July 28, 2012}}</ref>
* 2013: ''Oz'', based on ''[[The Wonderful Wizard of Oz]]''.<ref name="not in kansas anymore">{{cite news|last=Cropp|first=Avery|title={{'}}We're not in Kansas anymore{{'}}|url=http://stillwatergazette.com/2013/07/26/were-not-in-kansas-anymore/|accessdate=August 6, 2013|newspaper=Stillwater Gazette|date=July 26, 2013}}</ref> The performance retold [[Dorothy Gale]]'s travels through the [[Land of Oz]] and incorporated a "maison" trapeze, a cubic apparatus replicating Dorothy's house that gets swept away and carried to Oz by a tornado.<ref name="knight oz" />
* 2014: ''Neverland'', incorporating elements from the world of [[Peter and Wendy|Peter Pan]]<ref>{{cite news|last1=Beckstrom|first1=Maja|title=From the Art Crawl to the State Fair, 27 festivals to fill up your spring and summer|url=http://www.twincities.com/family/ci_25547244/family-events-twin-cities-your-guide|accessdate=April 26, 2014|newspaper=[[St. Paul Pioneer Press]]|date=April 11, 2014|first2=Amy Carlson|last2=Gustafson}}</ref> and featuring a [[Cradle (circus act)|cradle]] act.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Willms|first1=Jan|title=Aerial acts, triple trapeze, hoops, cradle-to-cradle, silks, triangle, theatre, and fire dance<U+2026> oh my!|url=http://www.longfellownokomismessenger.com/aerial-acts-triple-trapeze-hoops-cradle-to-cradle-silks-triangle-theatre-and-fire-dance-oh-my/|accessdate=October 2, 2014|work=Longfellow / Nokomis Messenger|date=August 2014|archivedate=August 12, 2014|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140812212233/http://www.longfellownokomismessenger.com/aerial-acts-triple-trapeze-hoops-cradle-to-cradle-silks-triangle-theatre-and-fire-dance-oh-my/}}</ref>
<gallery>
